Part 1 1. Make a histogram of the rating scores to visualize the overall distribution of scores. Change the number of bins from default to 10, 15, 20, and 25. Pick on the one that you think looks the best. Explain what the difference is when you change the number of bins and explain why you picked the one you did.

ggplot(chocolate, aes(x= rating))+
  geom_histogram(bins=25)+
  ggtitle("Distribution scores of chocolate rating")

#With 25 bins, the data is divided into smaller intervals, each bin covers a smaller set of values. With 10 bins, the data is divided into larger intervals, covering a larger range of values. I chose an interval of 25, because you are able to distinguish rating scores better. I feel that this gives more detail about the distribution of chocolate ratings.

7. For this last part, let’s explore the relationship between percent chocolate and ratings. Use the functions in dplyr, tidyr, and lubridate to perform the following steps to the chocolate dataset: 1. Identify the countries of bean origin with at least 50 reviews. Remove reviews from countries are not in this list. 2. Using the variable describing the chocolate percentage for each review, create a new column that groups chocolate percentages into one of four groups: (i) <60%, (ii) >=60 to <70%, (iii) >=70 to <90%, and (iii) >=90% (Hint check out the substr() function in base R and the case_when() function from dplyr – see example below). 3.Using the new column described in #2, re-order the factor levels (if needed) to be starting with the smallest percentage group and increasing to the largest percentage group (Hint check out the fct_relevel() function from forcats). 4.For each country, make a set of four side-by-side boxplots plotting the groups on the x-axis and the ratings on the y-axis. These plots should be faceted by country.

fiftyrevs<- chocolate %>%
  group_by(country_of_bean_origin) %>%
  summarise(
    total_reviews=n()
  )%>%
  filter(total_reviews>=50)

chocolate_50 <- chocolate %>%
  filter(country_of_bean_origin %in% fiftyrevs$country_of_bean_origin)
chocolate_50 <- chocolate_50 %>%
  mutate(
    cocoa_numeric = as.numeric(gsub("%", "", cocoa_percent)), 
    
    percent_group = case_when(
      cocoa_numeric < 60 ~ "<60%", 
      cocoa_numeric >= 60 & cocoa_numeric < 70 ~ ">=60 to <70%",
      cocoa_numeric >= 70 & cocoa_numeric < 90 ~ ">=70 to <90%",
      cocoa_numeric >= 90 ~ ">90%",
    ) %>%
    factor(levels = c("<60%", ">=60 to <70%",">=70 to <90%" , ">90%"))
  ) %>%
  arrange(percent_group)

Part 3. Convert wide into long data. Tasks We are going to create a set of features for us to plot over time. Use the functions in dplyr and tidyr to perform the following steps to the chocolate dataset:1.Create a new set of columns titled beans, sugar, cocoa_butter, vanilla, letchin, and salt that contain a 1 or 0 representing whether or not that review for the chocolate bar contained that ingredient (1) or not (0).2.Create a new set of columns titled char_cocoa, char_sweet, char_nutty, char_creamy, char_roasty, char_earthy that contain a 1 or 0 representing whether or not that the most memorable characteristic for the chocolate bar had that word (1) or not (0). For example, if the word “sweet” appears in the most_memorable_characteristics, then record a 1, otherwise a 0 for that review in the char_sweet column (Hint: check out str_detect() from the stringr package). 3.For each year (i.e. review_date), calculate the mean value in each new column you created across all reviews for that year. (Hint: If all has gone well thus far, you should have a dataset with 16 rows and 13 columns).4.Convert this wide dataset into a long dataset with a new feature and mean_score column.

chocolate_ingred <- chocolate %>%
  mutate(
    beans = ifelse(grepl("B", ingredients), 1, 0),
    sugar = ifelse(grepl("S", ingredients), 1, 0),
    cocoa_butter = ifelse(grepl("C", ingredients), 1, 0),
    vanilla = ifelse(grepl("V", ingredients), 1, 0),
    letchin = ifelse(grepl("L", ingredients), 1, 0),
    salt = ifelse(grepl("Sa", ingredients), 1, 0)  
  )
library(stringr)
chocolate_char <- chocolate_ingred %>%
  mutate(
    char_cocoa = ifelse(str_detect(most_memorable_characteristics, "cocoa"), 1, 0),
    char_sweet = ifelse(str_detect(most_memorable_characteristics, "sweet"), 1, 0),
    char_nutty = ifelse(str_detect(most_memorable_characteristics, "nutty"), 1, 0),
    char_creamy = ifelse(str_detect(most_memorable_characteristics, "creamy"), 1, 0),
    char_roasty = ifelse(str_detect(most_memorable_characteristics, "roasty"), 1, 0),
    char_earthy = ifelse(str_detect(most_memorable_characteristics, "earthy"), 1, 0)
  )
#sort by year, mean value of scores 
mean_values_year <- chocolate_char %>%
  group_by(review_date) %>%
  summarise(
    mean_beans = mean(beans),
    mean_sugar = mean(sugar),
    mean_cocoa_butter = mean(cocoa_butter),
    mean_vanilla = mean(vanilla),
    mean_letchin = mean(letchin),
    mean_salt = mean(salt),
    mean_char_cocoa = mean(char_cocoa),
    mean_char_sweet = mean(char_sweet),
    mean_char_nutty = mean(char_nutty),
    mean_char_creamy = mean(char_creamy),
    mean_char_roasty = mean(char_roasty),
    mean_char_earthy = mean(char_earthy)
  )

In this part of the project, we will continue to work with our now tidy song dataset from the previous part.Tasks:Use the functions in ggplot2 package to make a scatter plot of the mean_scores (y-axis) over time (x-axis). There should be one plot (facet) for each feature. For full credit, your plot should include:An overall title for the plot and a subtitle summarizing key trends that you found. Also include a caption in the figure with your name.Both the observed points for the mean_score, but also a smoothed non-linear pattern of the trend. All plots should be shown in the one figure. There should be an informative x-axis and y-axis label

ggplot(chocolate_long, aes(x = review_date, y = mean_score)) +
  geom_point() +  # Scatter points for mean scores
  geom_smooth(method = "loess", se = FALSE, color= "purple") +  # Smoothed non-linear trend
  labs(
    title = "Mean Scores Over Time by Feature of Chocolate",
     subtitle = str_wrap(" Mean scores of ingredients: lecithin, vanilla, and cocoa butter decrease over time. Generally, mean scores of the most memorable characteristics, creamy, decreased over time, while sweet and cocoa have increased in the last five years.", width = 80),
    caption = "Koko Hall",
    x = "Review Date (Year)",  
    y = "Mean Feature Scores" 
  ) +
  facet_wrap(~feature, scales = "free_y") +  # Facet for each feature
  theme_light()
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

1.The title is extremely small and not readable 2.The title is not informative. Titles help the viewer undrestand what the graph is about. 3.There are no y or x axis labels 4.The plot has a smoothed, non-linear line, but it is in white. It’s very hard to see the line. 5. The x-axis contains years that were before the study was conducted. There is a lot of unnecessary space. 6. The Y-axis is not scaled correctly, you aren’t able to observe the trend in the data 7. The caption is centerd with the creator’s name and is blocking the contents of the graph

Part 6. Make my plot a better plot! The goal is to take my sad looking plot and make it better! If you’d like an example, here is a tweet I came across of someone who gave a talk about how to zhoosh up your ggplots.

chocolate %>%
  ggplot(aes(
    x = as.factor(review_date),
    y = rating,
    fill = as.factor(review_date)  # Map fill to review_date
  )) +
  geom_violin(adjust = 1.5) +                            # Adjusted violin density for smoother plots
  scale_fill_manual(values = rainbow(length(unique(chocolate$review_date)))) +  # Use rainbow palette
  geom_boxplot(width = 0.1, color = "black", alpha = 0.5) +  # Overlay boxplots
  scale_x_discrete(breaks = seq(min(chocolate$review_date), max(chocolate$review_date), by = 5)) +    
  labs(
    title = "Chocolate Rating by Year",
    subtitle = str_wrap ("The range of chocolate ratings has narrowed over time. Medians scores have remained relatively stable ",  width = 80) ,
    x = "Review Year",
    y = "Rating",
    fill = "Review Year"
  ) +
  theme_minimal() +                                  # Apply a clean minimal theme
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))  # Rotate x-axis labels for better readability

1. I added a clear title to tell the reader what the graph was about 2. The x and y axes needed to be re-labelled 3. The years on the x axis were too crammed. I labelled the axis with less # of years 4. I tilted the x-axis years so they were more readable on the graph 5. The monochromatic blue was hard to distinguish the different years. Different colors per year were easier to follow. 6. I added a subtitle to describe the graph 7. I added boxplots to overlay the violin plots. We can measure the median and IQR values easier.
